@Node "MainView" "MainActor.guide/MainView"
@Next "Tutorial"
@Prev "The Arexx Interface"
@Toc "Main"

MainView
********

   MainView is MainActor's external player. It can display all
animations/pictures for which MainActor has the proper load modules.

   The key commands while playing animations or showing pictures are
the same as if you would view them directly with MainActor.  That is
the reason for not listing them here again, have a look at the
@{"Project Control Panel Window" Link "Project Control Panel Window"} under @{b}Play@{ub} and @{b}Show@{ub}.

   If MainActor saved an icon for the animations/pictures to view,
MainView will take the view settings from this icon (overruling its own
settings)!  You can change this behaviour through the @{b}IgnoreIcons@{ub}
option.

   MainView will use MainActors center option (which centers the
display of your animations or pictures) by default. If you specify an X
or Y Offset the center option will be disabled and the specified
offsets will be used instead.

   You can start MainView from the workbench or form the cli.

@{b}Starting MainView from the Workbench@{ub}

   If you start MainView from the Workbench (per icon), you can select
the file(s) to view in an ASL-requester. For multi selecting just press
one of the shift keys and select the files with the mouse. (Starting
from OS 2.1+)

MainView supports the following tooltypes:

@{i}Window@{ui}
     This tooltype enables the window mode, all animations or pictures
     will be displayed in a window on the current public screen.  It is
     disabled by default.

@{i}FrameInfo@{ui}
     FrameInfo enables the FrameInfo mode. It is disabled by default.

@{i}NoCaching@{ui}
     Disables caching. With caching disabled MainView plays direct from
     the harddisk (or whatever). This allows you to play big animations
     even if you have not much ram.  It is disabled by default.

@{i}IgnoreIcons@{ui}
     Ignores the icons of the animations/pictures It is disabled by
     default.

@{i}BBlank@{ui}
     Enables the BBlank option. It is disabled by default.

@{i}XOffset=<Value>@{ui}
     You can directly set the start x offset. 0 is the left border.  If
     you specify an XOffset centration will be disabled !

@{i}YOffset=<Value>@{ui}
     You can directly set the initial y offset. 0 is the top border.
     If you specify an YOffset centration will be disabled !

@{i}Repeat=<Value>@{ui}
     Repeats the animation <Value> times.  For example @{b}Repeat=1@{ub} would
     play the animation one time.  Defaults to 100.

@{i}Directory=<Path>@{ui}
     This is the initial directory for the ASL-requester.

@{i}Anim_Module=<Module>@{ui}
     Chooses the default load module for animations.  Default is the
     @{b}Universal@{ub} module.

@{i}Pic_Module=<Module>@{ui}
     Chooses the default load module for pictures.  Default is the
     @{b}Universal@{ub} module.  If you want to view all pictures for example on
     the Picasso-II gfx board, choose the @{b}Universal_PicassoII@{ub} module.

@{b}Starting MainView from the cli@{ub}

   Starting MainView from the CLI will give you enhanced functionality.
You can, for example, define patterns for animations or picture lists.

   Usage is : MainView [-<options>] <file>

   You can enter as many files as you like.

MainView supports these options :

     -w           : enables the window mode
     -fi          : enables the frameinfo option
     -nc          : turns caching off
     -i           : ignores the icons for the animations/pictures
     -bb          : enables the BorderBlank (BBlank) option
     -xvalue      : value describes the initial x offset
     -yvalue      : the same for the y offset.
     -rvalue      : value describes how often the animation
                    should be repeated
     -amodule     : where module is the default animation loader
                    for example @{b}-aUniversal@{ub} selects the universal
                    loader (default).
     -pmodule     : where module is the default picture loader
                    for example @{b}-aUniversal@{ub} selects the universal
                    loader (default).
                    If you want to remap your pictures to the
                    Picasso-II board enter @{b}-pUniversal_PicassoII@{ub}

Examples:

@{b}MainView -nc -r1 Graphics:Pics/#? Animation/#?8_32@{ub} will show all files
in the Graphics:Pics/ directory as well as all files in the Animation/
directory which end with '8_32' and all animations will be directly
played from the harddisk (one time).

@{b}MainView -pUniversal_PicassoII Graphics:#?_24Bit@{ub} will display all
pictures which names end with '_24Bit' on the Picasso-II board.


@EndNode

@Node "Tutorial" "MainActor.guide/Tutorial"
@Next "Tips and Tricks"
@Prev "MainView"
@Toc "Main"

Tutorial
********

   This tutorial will try to (quickly) explain the tasks you can
perform with MainActor.  It is just meant to give you the idea behind
MainActor, you still have to read all of the documentation to get the
most out of MainActor.

@{b}This tutorial will tell you how to@{ub}


 @{" Load Animations " Link "Load Animations"} 
 @{" Load Picture(s) " Link "Load Picture(s)"} 
 @{" Play Animations " Link "Play Animations"} 
 @{" Show Pictures " Link "Show Pictures"} 
 @{" Create-Convert Animations " Link "Create-Convert Animations"} 
 @{" Save Pictures From Animations " Link "Save Pictures From Animations"} 
 @{" Convert Picture Formats " Link "Convert Picture Formats"} 
 @{" Append To Animations " Link "Append To Animations"} 
 @{" Time Animations " Link "Time Animations"} 
 @{" Associate Sound Effects " Link "Associate Sound Effects"} 
 @{" Execute Arexx Scripts " Link "Execute Arexx Scripts"} 
 @{" Show Pics-Anims On Graphic Boards " Link "Show Pics-Anims On Graphic Boards"} 


@EndNode

@Node "Load Animations" "MainActor.guide/Load Animations"
@Next "Load Picture(s)"
@Toc "Tutorial"

Load Animations
===============

   You need an unused project to load an animation into MainActor.
Select the @{b}Select Load Module@{ub} gadget of the @{"Project Window" Link "Project Window"} and select
the proper animation format (if you, for example, want to load an
@{"IFF-Anim5" Link "IFF-Anim5"} animation, select the IFF-Anim5 loader or the Universal
loader).  If you want to cache the animation (buffer the animation in
memory), enable the @{b}Caching@{ub} gadget. Now select the @{b}Load@{ub} gadget of the
@{"Project Control Panel Window" Link "Project Control Panel Window"} and select the animation in the opening
ASL-requester. MainActor will now examine the animation and load it
into memory (if caching is enabled).  After that, the frames of the
animation are listed in the scroll list area of the project window,
also all gadgets (except the @{b}Load@{ub} and perhaps the @{b}Append@{ub} gadget) of the
Project Control Panel Window are now enabled.


@EndNode

@Node "Load Picture(s)" "MainActor.guide/Load Picture(s)"
@Next "Play Animations"
@Prev "Load Animations"
@Toc "Tutorial"

Load Picture(s)
===============

   You need an unused project to load a picture or a picture list into
MainActor.  Select the @{b}Select Load Module@{ub} gadget of the projects window
and select the proper picture format (if you, for example, want to load
an @{"IFF" Link "IFF"} picture, select the IFF loader).  If you want to cache the
picture(s) (buffer the picture(s) in memory), enable the @{b}Caching@{ub}
gadget. Now select the @{b}Load@{ub} gadget of the @{"Project Control Panel Window" Link "Project Control Panel Window"}
and select the first picture of the picture list in the opening
ASL-requester. If you want to load only one picture, you can cancel the
second requester, otherwise select the last picture of the picture list
in the second requester.  MainActor will now load the selected
picture(s) and buffer them into memory (if caching is enabled).  After
that, the picture(s) are listed in the scroll list area of the project
window, also all gadgets (except the @{b}Load@{ub} and @{b}Play@{ub} and perhaps the
@{b}Append@{ub} gadgets) of the Project Control Panel Window are now enabled.


@EndNode

@Node "Play Animations" "MainActor.guide/Play Animations"
@Next "Show Pictures"
@Prev "Load Picture(s)"
@Toc "Tutorial"

Play Animations
===============

   You have to load an animation first.  Just click on the @{b}Play@{ub} gadget
of the @{"Project Control Panel Window" Link "Project Control Panel Window"}.  For further details have a look
into the documentation.


@EndNode

@Node "Show Pictures" "MainActor.guide/Show Pictures"
@Next "Create-Convert Animations"
@Prev "Play Animations"
@Toc "Tutorial"

Show Pictures
=============

   You have to load an animation or a picture list first.  Select the
pictures you want to show in the source project's list view gadget,
after that simply press the @{b}Show@{ub} gadget of the
@{"Project Control Panel Window" Link "Project Control Panel Window"}.  For further details have a look into the
documentation.


@EndNode

@Node "Create-Convert Animations" "MainActor.guide/Create-Convert Animations"
@Next "Save Pictures From Animations"
@Prev "Show Pictures"
@Toc "Tutorial"

Create/Convert Animations
=========================

   You have to load an animation or a picture list first.  Select the
pictures which should be included in the new animation in the source
projects list view gadget. After that select the @{b}Select Save Module@{ub}
gadget and select the proper animation format.  Now click on the @{b}Save@{ub}
gadget of the @{"Project Control Panel Window" Link "Project Control Panel Window"} and enter the name of the
new animation.  MainActor will then create the animation, you may have
to answer some requesters (looping or non looping animation and so on).
For further details have a look into the documentation.


@EndNode

@Node "Save Pictures From Animations" "MainActor.guide/Save Pictures From Animations"
@Next "Convert Picture Formats"
@Prev "Create-Convert Animations"
@Toc "Tutorial"

Save Pictures From Animations
=============================

   The procedure is exactly the same as before, just select a picture
save module instead of an animation module.  For further details have a
look into the documentation.


@EndNode

@Node "Convert Picture Formats" "MainActor.guide/Convert Picture Formats"
@Next "Append To Animations"
@Prev "Save Pictures From Animations"
@Toc "Tutorial"

Convert Picture Formats
=======================

   The procedure is exactly the same as before, just load a picture or a
picture list and select another picture format's save module.


@EndNode

@Node "Append To Animations" "MainActor.guide/Append To Animations"
@Next "Time Animations"
@Prev "Convert Picture Formats"
@Toc "Tutorial"

Append To Animations
====================

   Load an animation or picture list into the source project and an
animation into the destination project.  The @{b}Append@{ub} gadget of the
@{"Project Control Panel Window" Link "Project Control Panel Window"} should now be enabled. Select the pictures
you want to append (to the destination project) in the source project.
After that select the @{b}Append@{ub} gadget, MainActor will now append the
selected pictures of the source project to the animation in the
destination project.  For further details have a look into the
documentation.


@EndNode

@Node "Time Animations" "MainActor.guide/Time Animations"
@Next "Associate Sound Effects"
@Prev "Append To Animations"
@Toc "Tutorial"

Time Animations
===============

   Load an animation and select the pictures you want to give a new
timecode.  Now select the @{b}Select Timecode@{ub} item in the @{"Miscellaneous Menu" Link "Miscellaneous Menu"}
and enter the new timecode into the integer gadget.  MainActor will now
write the new timecodes to the animation, you can check the new
timecodes by playing the animation.


@EndNode

@Node "Associate Sound Effects" "MainActor.guide/Associate Sound Effects"
@Next "Execute Arexx Scripts"
@Prev "Time Animations"
@Toc "Tutorial"

Associate Sound Effects
=======================

   Load an animation or picture (list) and select the @{b}Set Sound@{ub} function
of the @{"Miscellaneous Menu" Link "Miscellaneous Menu"}.

   Choose the @{b}Add Sound@{ub} gadget and select the picture for the sound
effect with the @{b}Choose Frame@{ub} gadget, select the sound module type with
the @{b}Choose Sound Module@{ub} gadget and choose the effect file itself trough
the @{b}Choose Sound Object@{ub} gadget.

   If you want to test the sound effect, just press on the @{b}Test@{ub} gadget.

   Now click on @{b}Ok@{ub} and play the animation.

   Load the supplied @{i}CountAnim7_32@{ui} animation in the @{i}Examples@{ui} directory
as example how to use the @{b}Sound Module Requester@{ub}.

   For further information have a look at the @{b}Set Sound@{ub} function and at
the @{"Sound Support" Link "Sound Support"} chapter.


@EndNode

@Node "Execute Arexx Scripts" "MainActor.guide/Execute Arexx Scripts"
@Next "Show Pics-Anims On Graphic Boards"
@Prev "Associate Sound Effects"
@Toc "Tutorial"

Execute Arexx Scripts
=====================

   You can directly execute arexx scripts by selecting the @{b}Start Arexx
Script@{ub} item in the @{"Arexx Menu" Link "Arexx Menu"} and selecting the arexx scripts.  You can
map arexx scripts to the function keys through the @{b}Install Arexx
Scripts@{ub} item (again in the Arexx Menu). You can really speed up
your work by using them, take a look at their header to get a short
description of what they do.


@EndNode

@Node "Show Pics-Anims On Graphic Boards" "MainActor.guide/Show Pics-Anims On Graphic Boards"
@Prev "Execute Arexx Scripts"
@Toc "Tutorial"

Show Pics/Anims On Graphic Boards
=================================

   Just use the proper universal module (like @{b}Universal_PicassoII@{ub}),
they remap the output of every module to the proper gxf board.  Note
that it is faster to view animations of the bitmap formats (like
Anim-5/7/8) on the native chipset as these formats have to be converted
to chunky pixel modes. Chunky pixel animation formats like FLI/FLC are
on the other hand faster on the graphic boards as on the native chip
set.


@EndNode

@Node "Tips and Tricks" "MainActor.guide/Tips and Tricks"
@Next "Registration"
@Prev "Tutorial"
@Toc "Main"

Tips and Tricks
***************

   @{b}*@{ub} Remember that the Amigas native display is bitmap based !  Chunky
     pixel based animation formats like FLI/FLC/DL or the GIF picture
     format have to be converted to bitmaps ! This is slow !  You have
     to have a chunky pixel based display (like the Picasso-II or
     Retina gfx cards) to be able to view them full speed (use the
     Universal_#? loader). On the other hand bitmap based formats like
     IFF-Anim5/7/8 are slow on these cards as they have to be converted
     from bitmap to chunky pixel.

   @{b}*@{ub} Always try to create animations with only one color palette per
     animation (CPA). They are faster than animations with color
     palettes per frame (CPF), especially if you have deeper (8-bit)
     displays.  CPF animations also have slower playback rates from hd.

   @{b}*@{ub} Remember that FLI and FLC animations are always identified as CPF
     animations, even if they dont have a color palette per every
     frame. Try to convert them to an CPA animation first if you are
     not sure if the color palette changes inside of the animation.

   @{b}*@{ub} IF you use the IFF-Anim7_16 or IFF-Anim8_16 animation savers,
     remember that the source frames should have a width which is
     divideable by 16 !  The same for the IFF-Anim7_32 and IFF-Anim8_32
     savers which need a width which is divideable by 32. If you ignore
     this, you will get a small area to the right of your screen which
     is not updated correctly.

   @{b}*@{ub} The preferences files are *SNAPSHOTS* of your current settup of
     MainActor, that means that if you save a prefs file and start
     MainActor later with it you will have exactly the same environment
     as before.


@EndNode

@Node "Registration" "MainActor.guide/Registration"
@Next "The Future"
@Prev "Tips and Tricks"
@Toc "Main"

Registration
************

   If you want to register MainActor you can choose between two
different packages :

Package One
     The registration fee for this package is @{b}$50@{ub} (85 german marks) or
     any aquivalent sum in your local currency.

     What you get for this package:

        @{b}*@{ub} A packet consisting of:

             - A TeX set, printed handbook

             - The latest version of MainActor

             - A keyfile

        @{b}*@{ub} Two free disk based updates (you have to contact me for your
          free updates)

        @{b}*@{ub} Additional updates are $20 (30 DM) with and $10 (15 DM)
          without a new handbook

Package Two
     The registration fee for this package is @{b}$25@{ub} (40 german marks) or
     any aquivalent sum in your local currency.

     What you get for this package:

        @{b}*@{ub} A packet consisting of:

             - The latest version of MainActor

             - A keyfile

        @{b}*@{ub} Additional updates are $20 (30 DM) with and $10 (15 DM)
          without a new handbook

@{b}How to order MainActor@{ub}

Germany
     If you live in germany, you can simply order your copy of MainActor
     per phone or fax

Europe
     If you live in europe, the best way is to send eurocheques, cash
     or directly transfer the money to our bank account.

Rest of the World
     If you dont live in europe, simply send us cash or transfer the
     money to our account. Note that we have to request a small fee for
     our bank costs. The price of MainActor for oversea transactions is
     $55 or $30.

     MainConcept, GbR Moenig/Zabel
     Im Johannistal 36
     52064 Aachen
     Germany
     
     Tel : 49 - 241- 707032
     FAX : 49 - 241- 707839
     BBS : 49 - 241- 707138

If you prefer direct transfer:

     MainConcept, GbR Moenig/Zabel
     NO. 20020251
     Sparkasse Aachen
     BLZ 390 500 00 (Germany)
     Usage: MainActor
     PLEASE INCLUDE YOUR NAME ON THE TRANSFER ORDER !!

If you have questions/suggestions feel free to contact us through email:

     Internet    zeus@jupiter.oche.de
     Internet    moenig@pool.informatik.rwth-aachen.de
     ADSP        markusm@tolkien.adsp.sub.org


@EndNode

@Node "The Future" "MainActor.guide/The Future"
@Next "Credits"
@Prev "Registration"
@Toc "Main"

The Future
**********

Future enhancements which are on my list:

   - An animation loader/saver for VRLIs Vista Pro format (VANIM).

   - More picture and animation modules (in general).

   - Far more arexx scripts (sinus (de)-acceleration scripts and more).

   - German documentation.

   - Special modules for commercial hardware (digitizers,gfx boards ..)
     are possible.

Your suggestions are always welcome.


@EndNode

